        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A&gt;</ph> property of a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline&gt;</ph> in order to control the repeat behavior of an animation.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A&gt;</ph> property of a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline&gt;</ph> controls how many times an animation repeats its simple duration.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>By using <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A&gt;</ph>, you can specify that a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline&gt;</ph> repeats for a certain number of times (an iteration count) or for a specified time period.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In either case, the animation goes through as many beginning-to-end runs that it needs in order to fill the requested count or duration.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>By default, timelines have a repeat count of 1.0, which means they play one time and do not repeat.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>However, if you set the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A&gt;</ph> property of a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline&gt;</ph> to <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.RepeatBehavior.Forever%2A&gt;</ph>, the timeline repeats indefinitely.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example shows how to use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A&gt;</ph> property to control the repeat behavior of an animation.</source>
        </trans-unit>
